{"cursor":"14005","size":15,"audio":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/d/db/Eve_of_Destruction_by_Barry_McGuire.ogg"],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox Single \n| Name = Eve of Destruction Cover = Eve-of-destruction.jpg Artist = Barry\n| McGuire from Album = Eve of Destruction A-side = B-side = Released = 1965\n| Format = 7\" Recorded = Genre = Folk rock Length = 3:38 Label = Dunhill\n| (U.S.) RCA (Canada) Writer = P. F. Sloan Producer = Lou Adler, P. F. Sloan,\n| Steve Barri Certification = Last single = \"Upon a Painted Ocean\" (1965)\n| This single = \"'Eve of Destruction'\" (1965) Next single = \"This Precious\n| Time\" (1965) Misc =\n{{Audiosample\n| Upper caption = Audio sample Audio file = Eve of Destruction by Barry\n| McGuire.ogg\n}} }}\n\n\"'Eve of Destruction'\" is a protest song written by P. F. Sloan in 1965. Several\nartists have recorded it, but the best-known recording was by Barry McGuire.\nThis recording was made between July 12 and July 15, 1965 and released by\nDunhill Records. The accompanying musicians were top-tier LA session players: P.\nF. Sloan on guitar, Hal Blaine (of Phil Spector's \"Wrecking Crew\") on drums, and\nLarry Knechtel on bass. The vocal track was thrown on as a rough mix and was not\nintended to be the final version, but a copy of the recording \"leaked\" out to a\nDJ, who began playing\nit. [http://www.xanga.com/barrymcguire/364332725/item.html Monday, 10\nOctober 2005 4.24 p.m. NZ time Eve ofâ¦ | barrymcguire's Xanga Site - Weblog ] The song was an instant hit and as a result the\nmore polished vocal track that was at first envisioned was never recorded.\n\nThe single hit #1 on the US Billboard Hot 100, and #3 on the UK Singles Chart.\n","linknr":300,"url":"Eve_of_Destruction_(song)","recorded":1375070109,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Eve_of_Destruction_(song)&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Eve_of_Destruction_(song)&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikiped